{"cursor":"26117","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox musical artist\n| image = Weather Report (Wayne Shorter).jpg name = Wayne Shorter caption =\n| Convocation Hall, Toronto, Nov. 27, 1977. Photo courtesy of Jean-Luc Ourlin\n| image_size = background = non_vocal_instrumentalist birth_name = alias =\n| birth_date = birth_place = Newark, New Jersey, United States death_date =\n| origin = instrument = Tenor saxophone, soprano saxophone genre = Modal jazz,\n| crossover jazz, post-bop, hard bop, jazz fusion, third stream occupation =\n| Saxophonist, composer years_active = 1958âpresent label = Blue Note, Columbia,\n| Verve associated_acts = Art Blakey, Miles Davis, Weather Report, Joni\n| Mitchell, John Pattitucci website = notable_instruments = Tenor and soprano\n| saxophones\n}}\n\n'Wayne Shorter' (born August 25, 1933) is an American jazz saxophonist\nand composer.\n\nJazz critic Ben Ratliff of the [[New York Times]] wrote that Shorter is\n\"generally acknowledged to be jazz's greatest living composer.\" Many of Shorter's compositions have become jazz standards.\nHis output has earned worldwide recognition, critical praise and various\ncommendations, including multiple Grammy Awards. [http://topics.nytimes.com-\n/topics/reference/timestopics/people/s/wayne_shorter/index.html The New York\nTimes: \"Times Topics\" listing]\n\nShorter first came to wide prominence in the late 1950s as a member of, and\neventually primary composer for, Art Blakey's Jazz Messengers. In the 1960s, he\nwent on to join Miles Davis's Second Great Quintet, and from there he co-founded\nthe jazz fusion band Weather Report. He has recorded over 20 albums as a\nbandleader.\n","linknr":502,"url":"Wayne_Shorter","recorded":1362567273,"links":47,"instances":["group","music","drummer","wayne_shorter_album","song","musician","music"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Modal jazz saxophonists","Crossover jazz saxophonists","Jazz fusion saxophonists","Hard bop saxophonists","Post-bop sax